hire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1415–":"from 10 January 1415 to 9 January 1416–Deceased","1386–Male":"1386–Deceased","1415–Male":"from10January1415to9January1416–Deceased","1432–1471":"1432–1471","1441–Male":"1441–Deceased","1449–Male":"1449–Deceased","1392–1421":"1392–1421","1415":"from 10 January 1415 to 9 January 1416","1421":"1421","1432":"1432","1441":"1441","1386":"1386","1471":"1471","1392":"1392","1449":"1449","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from one or more of several places so named, such as Walford (Herefordshire), Walford in Leintwardine (also Herefordshire), Walford in Baschurch (Shropshire), and possibly Walford Hall in Hampton in Arden (Warwickshire), though this last may be a manorial placename deriving from the surname. The Herefordshire placenames probably derive from Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Welshman’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. The Shropshire placename derives from Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + <i>ford</i>. If it does not derive from the surname, the Warwickshire placename probably has the same etymology as the Herefordshire placenames.","perhaps occasionally a habitational name from Walford in Wimborne Minster (Dorset). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>walt</i> ‘unsteady’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Walford was born from 10 January 1415 to 9 January 1416, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of William Walford. He had at least 3 sons."},"et":{"1415–":"10. jaanuar 1415 kuni 9. jaanuar 1416–Surnud","1386–Male":"1386–Surnud","1415–Male":"10.jaanuar1415kuni9.jaanuar1416–Surnud","1432–1471":"1432–1471","1441–Male":"1441–Surnud","1449–Male":"1449–Surnud","1392–1421":"1392–1421","1415":"10. jaanuar 1415 kuni 9. jaanuar 1416","1421":"1421","1432":"1432","1441":"1441","1386":"1386","1471":"1471","1392":"1392","1449":"1449","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1415–":"vuodesta 10. tammikuuta 1415 vuoteen 9. tammikuuta 1416–Kuollut","1386–Male":"1386–Kuollut","1415–Male":"vuodesta10.tammikuuta1415vuoteen9.tammikuuta1416–Kuollut","1432–1471":"1432–1471","1441–Male":"1441–Kuollut","1449–Male":"1449–Kuollut","1392–1421":"1392–1421","1415":"vuodesta 10. tammikuuta 1415 vuoteen 9. tammikuuta 1416","1421":"1421","1432":"1432","1441":"1441","1386":"1386","1471":"1471","1392":"1392","1449":"1449","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1415–":"du 10 janvier 1415 au 9 janvier 1416–Décédé","1386–Male":"1386–Décédé","1415–Male":"du10janvier1415au9janvier1416–Décédé","1432–1471":"1432–1471","1441–Male":"1441–Décédé","1449–Male":"1449–Décédé","1392–1421":"1392–1421",